description:
The Moroccan authorities announced the 23rd of April 2020  in the context of the "state of health emergency" a "Night movement ban" from the 1st Ramadan/ Saturday 25th April from 7 PM to 5 AM, giving the exception to: 
-Medics and paramedics;
-Public authorities, army forces, and police;
-People with medical emergencies;
-Night workers with a proof certificate from their institutions;
-Religious curators charged with raising the call to prayer in mosques.

The Moroccan authorities announced the 23rd of April 2020  in the context of the "state of health emergency" a "Night movement ban" from the 1st Ramadan/ Saturday 25th April from 7 PM to 5 AM and ends on the 25 of May, giving the exception to: 
-Medics and paramedics;
-Public authorities, army forces, and police;
-People with medical emergencies;
-Night workers with a proof certificate from their institutions;
-Religious curators charged with raising the call to prayer in mosques.
 UPDATE: The "night movement ban" started 1st Ramadan/ 25th April from 7 pm to 5 am, ended on the 25th of May.

On the 31st of August Morocco's Ministry of Health announced it is putting in place "within three days" new measures to ensure the reliability of COVID-19 tests, including through:
- Rigorous verification of reagents for in vitro diagnostic use by subjecting them to evaluation by designated laboratories;
- Control of laboratory activities through unannounced visits and by conducting external assessment of the quality of the analysis;
- Approval for authorized laboratories to carry out diagnostic tests for people traveling abroad at the level of each province;
- Exclusive use of the Ministry's "E-Labs" platform by these laboratories for the centralization and communication of test results;
- Downloading of the results of the Covid-19 tests by people traveling abroad via the "Pass-sanitaire" option which will be available on the liqahcorona.ma portal.
